## Chat-A2 Chat-Turn Agent Handoff Architecture
**Status:** proposed
**Tags:** stack:both
**Depends on:** Chat-G6, Relay-G9

The relay pipeline (Relay-A1) uses formal `HandoffDocument` generation between steps, but the free-form chat flow has no handoff mechanism. The assistant (Nicole) classifies user intent but cannot act on that classification — she answers everything herself with all tools. The bring-in tool bridges this gap by letting Nicole invoke another agent mid-conversation, passing structured context so the receiving agent doesn't ask the user to repeat.

```mermaid
graph LR
    U[User Message] --> N[Nicole: Assistant]
    N -->|classify| D{Intent?}
    D -->|QUESTION| AN[Nicole answers]
    D -->|DIRECT| AN
    D -->|NEW_GOAL| B[bring_in tool]
    D -->|REQ_UPDATE| B
    B -->|handoff note| I[Isaac: Advisor]
    I -->|continue chat| U
    B -->|handoff note| ASH[Ash: Coder]
    ASH -->|continue chat| U
```

| Approach | Pros | Cons |
|---|---|---|
| bring_in tool with handoff note (chosen) | Seamless, no user action needed, context preserved | LLM must reliably call the tool; adds tool to ReAct loop |
| Suggest + user @mentions | Simple, no new tool | Nicole can't act autonomously; user must remember to @mention |
| Automatic backend routing based on classification | No LLM tool call needed | Requires structured classification output; brittle |

- Positive: Nicole acts as a real dispatcher — she connects users to the right specialist.
- Positive: Handoff note preserves context, so the next agent starts informed.
- Positive: Frontend shows a visual handoff card, not raw tool output.
- Negative: LLM must reliably call bring_in with correct target; may need prompt tuning.
- Mitigation: Nicole's soul already instructs classification; bring_in is the natural action after classification. Validation rejects invalid targets (not in handoff_to).

